"title": "Layered Optimized Architecture for AI-Integrated Systems",
"summary": "Version 0.5 — A reference for human architects and AI code-generation assistants",
"path": "pack/knowledge/layered-optimized-architecture.md",
"kind": "knowledge",
"text": "layered optimized architecture for ai-integrated systems version 0.5 — a reference for human architects and ai code-generation assistants layered optimized architecture for ai-integrated systems principles, archetypes, and a pattern catalog abstract reading guide changelog foreword the loa metamodel part i — the frame the capability–cost surface why classical layering is insufficient part ii — principles part iii — canonical architecture archetypes archetype a — cascade pipeline archetype b — adversarial ensemble archetype c — tool-mediated constructor archetype d — grounded synthesizer archetype e — generate-verify-select loop archetype f — copilot aside hot path archetype g — continuous sentinel archetype h — long-horizon agent archetype i — multimodal pipeline part iv — pattern catalog category 1 — routing & composition pattern 1.1: capability router pattern 1.2: cascade pattern 1.3: plan/execute split pattern 1.4: hot path bypass pattern 1.5: hierarchical decomposition pattern 1.6: speculative execution pattern 1.7: computer-use / gui agent category 2 — cost optimization pattern 2.1: semantic cache pattern 2.2: prompt prefix cache pattern 2.3: distillation loop pattern 2.4: token budget throttle pattern 2.5: schema-constrained output pattern 2.6: test-time compute budget category 3 — verification pattern 3.1: deterministic verifier pattern 3.2: adversarial debater pattern 3.3: prover agent pattern 3.4: red team probe pattern 3.5: self-consistency pattern 3.6: reflection (self-critique) category 4 — state & context pattern 4.1: grounded context injector pattern 4.2: tool-mediated state pattern 4.3: receipt ledger pattern 4.4: memory (working / episodic / semantic) pattern 4.5: hybrid retrieval category 5 — tool integration pattern 5.1: typed tool surface pattern 5.2: sandboxed executor pattern 5.3: idempotent action category 6 — quality & safety pattern 6.1: capability escalator pattern 6.2: guardrail filter pattern 6.3: audit trail pattern 6.4: confidence-calibrated gating pattern 6.5: graceful degradation pattern 6.6: provider portability part v — composition examples composition a — day-trader / cfd application (copilot aside hot path) composition b — cloud incident dri (continuous sentinel + adversarial ensemble) composition c — compliance across the dev loop (continuous sentinel) composition d — software engineering agent (long-horizon agent) composition e — document understanding (multimodal pipeline) part vi — guidance for ai code generation part vii — conformance criteria part viii — decision framework archetype selection table pattern selection rules tier budgeting heuristic part ix — evaluation harness components architectural placement conformance appendix a — pattern quick reference appendix b — archetype-to-pattern mapping appendix c — anti-patterns with severity and detection criteria appendix d — .net / c# idiom map wiring example: composing a loa service in `program.cs` appendix e — glossary appendix f — architecture decision record (adr) template adr-nnnn: [decision title] context decision loa mapping conformance impact alternatives considered consequences cost model appendix g — reference roslyn analyzers c2 — budget propagation analyzer c5 — side-effect protection analyzer c6 — idempotency-key analyzer appendix h — system-level cost model per-archetype cost formulas distillation effect worked example: composition b (cloud incident dri) appendix i — per-pattern cost-impact table category 1 — routing & composition category 2 — cost optimization category 3 — verification category 4 — state & context category 5 — tool integration category 6 — quality & safety reading the table together appendix j — reference roslyn analyzer package appendix k — reference implementation: composition b # layered optimized architecture for ai-integrated systems ## principles, archetypes, and a pattern catalog *version 0.5 — a reference for human architects and ai code-generation assistants* --- ## abstract layered optimized architecture (loa) is a frame for designing ai-integrated systems under a constraint classical architecture did not face: **per-call inference cost varies by three to five orders of magnitude across the available computational substrate**, with capability, latency, and determinism profiles that map non-linearly to that cost. loa treats the *capability tier* as an architectural dimension orthogonal to classical technical layering, and supplies a small set of principles, a catalog of canonical architectural shapes, and a pattern catalog with reference c# implementations and reference roslyn analyzers. it is intended for both human architects and ai code-generation assistants, and includes mechanically checkable conformance criteria with rfc 2119 normative language. ## reading guide this document is approximately twelve thousand words and serves several audiences. each can navigate efficiently: - **architects making technology decisions** should read the abstract, the metamodel, part i (the frame), part ii (principles), part iii (archetypes), and part viii (decision framework). parts iv and beyond become reference material. - **developers implementing components** should skim parts ii and iii for context, then work primarily from part iv (pattern catalog) and appendix d (.net idiom map). appendix g provides reference roslyn analyzers. - **ai code-generation assistants** loaded with this document as context should treat parts ii, iv, vi, and vii as the operational core. conformance criteria in part vii are the test suite. - **reviewers and auditors** should read the abstract, part vii (conformance), appendix c (anti-patterns with detection criteria), and appendix f (adr template). - **finance and budget partners** should read the abstract, part i, and appendix h (system-level cost model). cross-references use the form *pattern 3.2 adversarial debater* on first mention within a section and *(3.2)* thereafter. archetypes use letters a–i; patterns use numerals x.y by…"
